Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".

This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

The DT Sport proved to be one hundred percent reliable, as expected. The carbine fed, fired, and ejected every cartridge perfectly. The DT Sport has everything that you need, and nothing that you don’t. It performs as well as rifles costing three times the price, and buying a basic rifle such as this leaves a lot more cash to purchase a good optic, plenty of extra magazines, and ammunition. ((WTT)) I have a Stoeger M2000 in a black synthetic stock. Its take 12 gauge 2 3/4" - 3" shells. For those who dont know what a Stoeger shotgun is....
"Stoeger is a Turkish made semi- auto shotgun. It is based on benelli's inertia system which has proven to be extremely reliable in harsh hunting conditions. As opposed to a gas systems which use gases from the firing of the shotgun to cycle the action, the inertia systm uses the recoil and the actual force from the discharged shell to cycle it. Since there are no gases escaping or being used they are known for being extremely "clean" guns. Meaning they can go long periods without cleaning. Some people feel there is more felt recoil than in a gas gun but trade that off for the reliability. Similar guns are the benelli m2 and franchi I12. Both are considerabley more expensive and made in Italy."

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt 1911 - Year 1918 - Original with accessories
postcontent:
An absolutely priceless piece of American history, almost 100 years old and shoots great. I've been doing research on this beautiful gun and this is a summary of what ive put together: It was ordered by the Army during WWI and manufactured in the third fiscal quarter of 1918. The 333XXX serial number indicates it was built after Colt started doing the Black finish, which is consistent with the way the finish looks and has worn, and it shows no arsenal rebuild marks. It was later issued with its original magazine to a Marine Naval Aviator and carried during WWII in the Pacific Theatre with an additional 2 magazines made as part of a Colt contract by a company called Risdon. As was possible at the time, the service member chose to purchase the gun from the government and took it home back home, in this case Pensacola, FL. It was then put away in condition 1, in its holster with 7 rounds of Federal ammo manufactured in 1942. 

I came across this gun at the estate sale of the son of the aforementioned Marine. I have the gun, the holster, the original WWI magazine, the 2 WWII magazines, the black USMC stamped holster, and the 7 rounds it was stored with for 70 years (which have developed a fascinating patina on the copper jacket). After getting it, I inspected it, cleaned it, lubed it and being impressed by the condition, I put 140 rounds of 230 gr fmj through it without a single hiccup using the WWI and WWII magazines. It does hand cycle wwb jhp, but I have not fired any. It has fired perfectly for me and is a true testament to old American craftsmanship and the perfection of JMB's design.
As can be imagined with a gun that is almost 100 years old and was carried in at least one if not both World Wars, it is not perfect. It has some scratches around the slide stop and the hammer was slightly shortened (to prevent hammer bite, which was an issue later addressed with the A1 at the request of our veterans). Also, the WWI magazine does not drop free, but otherwise functions perfectly. There is no rust anywhere on it, the barrel rifling is sharp and it shoots almost as well as my Kimbers. I believe that the difference is in the sights and not in the accuracy of the gun itself. It has a real soul that you can feel when you hold it. It sounds strange but it is the only way I can explain how it feels. 

I can send more pictures upon request. I'm more than happy to show the gun to serious prospective buyers, or even meet at the range for test shooting. 
Happy to ship to your friendly local FFL if necessary. 
I am asking $1999 for the complete package:
The gun itself is valued at $2050 according to the 33rd Edition of Fjestad's Blue Book of Gun Values. The rare holster is valued at $200, the WWI mag at $100, and each of the WWII mags at $50 each, for a total value of $2450. I am selling it because I am not a collector, I could use some cash right now, and I believe it could be truly appreciated for everything that it is as the crown jewel to the right collection.

If you are interested please feel free to contact me anytime day or night. Text preferred. 
REDACTED
